program primes
  implicit none
  integer :: i, j, n, isprime(100)

  ! initialize array to all ones
  isprime = 1

  ! sieve of eratosthenes
  do i = 2, 100
    if (isprime(i) == 1) then
      do j = 2, 100 / i
        isprime(i*j) = 0
      end do
    end if
  end do

  ! print out primes
  do i = 2, 100
    if (isprime(i) == 1) then
      print *, i
    end if
  end do

end program primes

! Optical system with 2 lenses of focal 150mm and 400mm
! Analysis of sensibility and aberrations with OptoCAD
! Output file in ".ps" format

PROGRAM OptoCAD_analysis
  IMPLICIT NONE

  ! Declare variables
  INTEGER, PARAMETER :: npts = 100
  REAL, PARAMETER :: F1 = 150.0, F2 = 400.0
  REAL, DIMENSION(npts) :: X, Y1, Y2, paraxial, yS, angle
  INTEGER :: i

  ! Initialize variables
  DO i = 1, npts
    X(i) = (i - 1)*0.01
    angle(i) = ASIN(X(i))
    paraxial(i) = F1*TAN(angle(i))
    yS(i) = F1 - F2
    Y1(i) = paraxial(i) + yS(i)
    Y2(i) = Y1(i) + F2*TAN(angle(i))
  END DO

  ! Output data to a file
  OPEN(UNIT=10, FILE="OptoCAD_output.dat", STATUS="REPLACE")
  DO i = 1, npts
    WRITE(10,*) X(i), Y1(i), Y2(i)
  END DO
  CLOSE(UNIT=10)

  ! Generate the output .ps file
  CALL GeneratePSfile()

CONTAINS
  SUBROUTINE GeneratePSfile()
    ! The Gnuplot command needs to be adapted to your specific installation and data filenames
    CALL SYSTEM("gnuplot -e " &
      "'set terminal postscript; " &
      "set output \"OptoCAD_graph.ps\"; " &
      "set xlabel \"X\"; " &
      "set ylabel \"Y\"; " &
      "set title \"Sensibility and Aberration Analysis\"; " &
      "plot \"OptoCAD_output.dat\" using 1:2 title \"Lens 1\" with lines, " &
      "\"OptoCAD_output.dat\" using 1:3 title \"Lens 2\" with lines'")
  ENDSUBROUTINE GeneratePSfile

ENDPROGRAM OptoCAD_analysis

Ausgewählte Tage im Jahr = 
VAR AktuellesJahr = YEAR(MAX('Kalender'[Datum]))
VAR StartDatum = DATE(AktuellesJahr, 1, 1)
VAR EndDatum = DATE(AktuellesJahr, 12, 31)
VAR AusgewählteDaten =
    CALCULATETABLE (
        'Kalender',
        'Kalender'[Datum] >= StartDatum,
        'Kalender'[Datum] <= EndDatum,
        ALLSELECTED('Kalender'[Datum])
    )
RETURN COUNTROWS(AusgewählteDaten)

  first = 0
  second = 1
  write(*,*) first
  write(*,*) second
  do i=3,20
    next = first + second
    write(*,*) next
    first = second
    second = next
  end do

PROGRAM ctg_table
  IMPLICIT NONE

  INTEGER, PARAMETER :: data_len = 1024
  CHARACTER (LEN=data_len) :: data_line
  REAL :: x_min, x_max, x_step, y_min, y_max, y_step
  INTEGER :: n, m, i, j
  REAL, ALLOCATABLE :: x_values(:), y_values(:), func_val(:,:)
  REAL :: angle

  INQUIRE (FILE='input.txt', EXIST=exist)
  IF (.NOT. exist) THEN
    PRINT *, 'input.txt not found.'
    STOP
  ENDIF

  OPEN (UNIT=10, FILE='input.txt', STATUS='OLD', ACTION='READ')
    READ (10, *) x_min, x_max, x_step
    READ (10, *) y_min, y_max, y_step
  CLOSE (10)

  IF ((x_min >= x_max) .OR. (y_min >= y_max) .OR. (x_step <= 0) .OR. (y_step <= 0)) THEN
    PRINT *, 'Invalid input parameters.'
    STOP
  ENDIF

  n = CEILING((x_max - x_min) / x_step)
  m = CEILING((y_max - y_min) / y_step)

  ALLOCATE (x_values(n+1), y_values(m+1), func_val(m+1, n+1))

  DO i = 0, n
    x_values(i+1) = x_min + i * x_step
    IF (x_values(i+1) > x_max) THEN
      x_values(i+1) = x_max
    ENDIF
  END DO

  DO i = 0, m
    y_values(i+1) = y_min + i * y_step
    IF (y_values(i+1) > y_max) THEN
      y_values(i+1) = y_max
    ENDIF
  END DO

  DO i = 1, m+1
    DO j = 1, n+1
      angle = x_values(j) + y_values(i)
      IF (MOD(angle, 180) == 0) THEN
        PRINT *, 'Ctg(x + y) is not defined at angle ', angle
        func_val(i,j) = 0.0
      ELSE
        func_val(i,j) = 1.0 / TAN(angle * 3.14159265 / 180.0)
      ENDIF
    END DO
  END DO

  OPEN (UNIT=11, FILE='output.txt', STATUS='REPLACE', ACTION='WRITE')
    WRITE (11, *) '|     |',
    DO i = 1, n+1
      WRITE (11, '(F10.4, A)', ADVANCE='NO') x_values(i), ' |'
    END DO
    WRITE (11, *)

    DO i = 1, m+1
      WRITE (11, '(F10.4, A)', ADVANCE='NO') y_values(i), ' |'
        DO j = 1, n+1
          IF (func_val(i,j) /= 0) THEN
            WRITE (11, '(F10.4, A)', ADVANCE='NO') func_val(i,j), ' |'
          ELSE
            WRITE (11, '(10A1, A)', ADVANCE='NO') ' not def.  |'
          ENDIF
        END DO
      WRITE (11, *)
    END DO
  CLOSE (11)

  DEALLOCATE (x_values, y_values, func_val)

  PRINT *, 'Ctg(x + y) table has been successfully generated in output.txt'
  
END PROGRAM ctg_table

PROGRAM COTANGENT_TABLE
      IMPLICIT none
      REAL XMIN, XMAX, XSTEP, YMIN, YMAX, YSTEP, PI
      INTEGER N, M, I, J
      CHARACTER*10 NOT_DEFINED
      PARAMETER (PI = 3.14159265)
      PARAMETER (NOT_DEFINED = 'UNDEFINED')
      REAL XVALUES(100), YVALUES(100), TANVALUES(100, 100)
      CHARACTER*12 XLABELS(101), YLABELS(101)
      OPEN(UNIT=10, FILE='input.dat', STATUS='old')
      OPEN(UNIT=20, FILE='output.txt', STATUS='unknown')
      READ(10, *) XMIN, XMAX, XSTEP
      READ(10, *) YMIN, YMAX, YSTEP
      CLOSE(UNIT=10)
      IF(XMIN > XMAX .or. YMIN > YMAX .or. XSTEP <= 0.0 .or. YSTEP <= 0.0) THEN
         WRITE(*, *) 'ERROR: Invalid input parameters'
         STOP
      END IF
      N = (XMAX - XMIN) / XSTEP
      M = (YMAX - YMIN) / YSTEP
      DO I = 0, N
         XVALUES(I) = XMIN + I * XSTEP
      END DO
      DO J = 0, M
         YVALUES(J) = YMIN + J * YSTEP
      END DO
      DO I = 0, N
         DO J = 0, M
            IF(COS(XVALUES(I) + YVALUES(J)) == 0.0) THEN
               TANVALUES(I, J) = 0.0
            ELSE
               TANVALUES(I, J) = -SIN(XVALUES(I) + YVALUES(J)) / 
     $                           COS(XVALUES(I) + YVALUES(J))
            END IF
         END DO
      END DO
      WRITE(20, '(1X, A, 1X, (|, 1X, A12, 1X)')) 'Y\X', 
     $      (YLABELS(I), I = 0, N)
      DO J = 0, M
         WRITE(20, '(A8, 1X, (|, 1X, 1PF12.3, 1X))') YLABELS(J),
     $         (IF(TANVALUES(I, J) == 0.0) THEN (NOT_DEFINED) 
     $          ELSE (TANVALUES(I, J)), I = 0, N)
      END DO
      CLOSE(UNIT=20)
      STOP
      END

LOCAL lcCSVFile, lcDBFFile, lnCols, lcLine, lcValue

lcCSVFile = "YourCSVFile.csv"  && путь и имя CSV-файла
lcDBFFile = "YourDBFFile.dbf"  && путь и имя DBF-файла

* открыть CSV-файл и прочитать его построчно
lnCols = 0 && количество колонок в csv-файле, предполагаем, что количество колонок одинаково для всех строк
lnHandle = FOPEN(lcCSVFile, 1)
IF lnHandle > 0
    DO WHILE NOT FEOF(lnHandle)
        lcLine = FGETS(lnHandle)
        lnCols = FCOUNT(lcLine, ";")
        IF lnCols > 0  && предполагаем, что строка содержит данные
            lcValue = ""
            FOR lnColNo = 1 TO lnCols
                lcValue = lcValue + TRANSFORM(STRGET(lcLine, lnColNo, ";")) + IIF(lnColNo < lnCols, ",", "")
            ENDFOR
            * добавить строку в DBF-файл
            APPEND FROM (lcValue) TYPE DELIMITED WITH DELIMITER ","  TO (lcDBFFile)
        ENDIF
    ENDDO
    FCLOSE(lnHandle)
ENDIF

program RandomAtomDeletion

    implicit none
    
    integer, parameter :: N = 10            ! 原子总数
    integer, parameter :: deleted_atoms = 3 ! 删除的原子数
    
    integer :: i, j, k
    integer, dimension(N) :: atoms
    logical, dimension(N) :: deleted
    
    ! 初始化原子数组和删除标记数组
    atoms = (/ (i, i=1,N) /)
    deleted = .false.
    
    ! 随机删除原子
    do i = 1, deleted_atoms
        ! 生成一个随机数来选择要删除的原子
        j = int(N * rand())
        
        ! 如果原子未被删除，则删除它
        if (.not. deleted(j)) then
            deleted(j) = .true.
            write(*, "(A,I3,A)") "删除了原子 ", j, "!"
        else
            ! 如果已删除该原子，则递增选择索引，直到找到一个未被删除的原子
            k = j
            do while (deleted(k))
                k = k + 1
                if (k > N) k = 1 ! 索引循环
            end do
            deleted(k) = .true.
            write(*, "(A,I3,A,I3,A)") "删除了原子 ", j, "，删除了第 ", i, " 个原子!"
        end if
    end do
    
    ! 打印剩余的原子
    write(*, "(A)") "剩余的原子:"
    do i = 1, N
        if (.not. deleted(i)) write(*, "(I3)") atoms(i)
    end do
    
end program RandomAtomDeletion

I want to share with you the truth about those days when you used to babysit these girls. I had a mindset that I inherited from our parents, a toxic belief that some people were worth liking while others deserved my hate. And I acted upon it, hurting innocent girls like Jane.

Looking back, I find it horrifying that I actually enjoyed being mean to them. It fueled a sense of power within me, a twisted satisfaction that brought me temporary relief from my own pain. I only agreed to babysit for the extra cash, believing that connection or kindness were unnecessary. But I can't ignore the fact that I genuinely liked some, like Sam. Perhaps it was because she reminded me of our kinder self amidst the turmoil.

Please know that during those times, I was mentally unstable and struggling. Our mind was a battlefield, and the inner chaos nearly swallowed me whole. The pain became unbearable, and I made six attempts to end my own life. Somehow, I failed each time, a reminder that deep down, there was a will to live.

Reflecting upon it now, I regret the dark mindset that led me to hurt these girls. I was lost, consumed by my own demons. I wish I could have been there for them with kindness, compassion, and understanding. They deserved better.

I hope that one day, you may find it in your heart to forgive yourself and seek forgiveness from those you've hurt. Seek help. Talk to someone you trust about your struggles. It may be a long and difficult journey, but perhaps redemption and healing are possible.

With deepest regrets,
Your older self

Naive filters work in quadratic time, i.e. the time needed increases with the square of the number if visits for dictionary roots or smoothing counts.

The Vectorization pipeline should have hyperparameters how many features it passes, or how many words to keep (e.g., via `max_feature=3000`).
We also do not know which classifier you are using. Some of them don't tolerate unnormalized data well. Some will put too much importance on rare frequent words, like "the".

In my hypothesis, I stated that the height from which a ball is dropped will directly affect the height to which it bounces back up. Additionally, I postulated that the hardness of the surface it lands on will impact its bouncing ability. However, I did not specifically address the concept of bounce efficiency.

Upon conducting the investigation, I have obtained key results that support my hypothesis. The experiments consistently demonstrated that when the ball was dropped from a greater height, it indeed bounced back up higher. This observation confirms the relationship between the drop height and the height of the rebound.

Furthermore, I noticed that the bounce efficiency of the ball varied depending on the drop height. Surprisingly, even though the ball did not reach higher heights when dropped from lower positions, the bounce efficiency was found to be greater. This suggests that the ball was able to convert a higher percentage of its initial kinetic energy into potential energy during these lower drops.

Overall, the results of this investigation validate my hypothesis. The drop height plays a crucial role in determining the bounce height, and the hardness of the surface influences the ball's ability to bounce. Additionally, considering the bounce efficiency provides insights into the energy conversion process during rebound. These findings contribute to a deeper understanding of the physics behind ball bouncing and are important in various practical applications.

In my hypothesis, I stated the following: "The higher the ball is dropped from, the higher it will bounce back up. The harder the surface, the more it will bounce." 

To test this hypothesis, I conducted a thorough investigation and collected key results. Consistently, throughout the experiments, I observed that when the ball was dropped from a greater height, it indeed bounced back up to a higher extent. This finding supports the initial claim that the height from which the ball is dropped directly affects its bouncing height. 

Alongside the impact of drop height, I also examined the influence of surface hardness on the ball's bouncing ability. Although not mentioned explicitly in the hypothesis, I discovered that the bounce efficiency varied depending on the height of the drop. Surprisingly, the ball demonstrated greater bounce efficiency when dropped from a lower height, despite not reaching as high as when dropped from a higher position. This finding highlights the interplay between drop height, surface hardness, and bounce efficiency.

In conclusion, the investigation provides substantial evidence to support the initial hypothesis. The drop height significantly affects the bouncing height, with higher drops yielding higher rebounds. Additionally, the interaction between drop height and surface hardness affects the bounce efficiency. These findings contribute to a better understanding of the physics underlying ball bouncing and have important implications in various practical applications.

CREATE PROCEDURE CheckOddness
    @Number INT,
    @IsOdd BIT OUTPUT
AS
BEGIN
    IF (@Number % 2 = 1)
        SET @IsOdd = 1
    ELSE
        SET @IsOdd = 0
END

CREATE PROCEDURE CheckPrime
    @Number INT,
    @IsPrime BIT OUTPUT
AS
BEGIN
    SET @IsPrime = 1
    IF @Number <= 1
        SET @IsPrime = 0
    ELSE
    BEGIN
        DECLARE @Counter INT = 2

        WHILE (@Counter < @Number)
        BEGIN
            IF (@Number % @Counter = 0)
            BEGIN
                SET @IsPrime = 0
                BREAK
            END

            SET @Counter = @Counter + 1
        END
    END
END

A = rand(33, 33);  % 33*33矩阵A
B = rand(33, 1);   % 33*1矩阵B
C = 0.5;           % 设定值C

D = zeros(33, 2);  % 存储结果的矩阵D

for i = 1:33
    % 计算A的第i行大于设定值C的和
    if any(A(i, :) > C)
        D(i, 1) = sum(A(i, A(i, :) > C) .* B(A(i, :) > C));
    end
    
    % 计算A的第i行小于等于设定值C的和
    if any(A(i, :) <= C)
        D(i, 2) = sum(A(i, A(i, :) <= C) .* B(A(i, :) <= C));
    end
end

program BinaryToDecimal
  implicit none
  
  character(20) :: binaryString
  integer :: binaryNumber, decimalNumber, i, len
  
  write(*,*) "Введите число в двоичной системе счисления: "
  read(*,*) binaryString
  
  len = len_trim(binaryString)
  decimalNumber = 0
  
  do i = 1, len
    binaryNumber = val(binaryString(i:i:i))
    if (binaryNumber /= 0 .and. binaryNumber /= 1) then
      write(*,*) "Ошибка: введено не двоичное число."
      stop
    end if
    
    decimalNumber = decimalNumber * 2 + binaryNumber
  end do
  
  write(*,*) "Число в десятичной системе счисления: ", decimalNumber
  
end program BinaryToDecimal

    real :: x, energy, sigma, x0, k0, psi_real, psi_imag

    ! Παράμετροι για την κυματοσυνάρτηση
    sigma = 1.0
    x0 = 0.0
    k0 = 1.0

    ! Έλεγχος για κάθε τιμή του x
    do x = -15, 15, 0.5
        ! Υπολογισμός της δυναμικής ενέργειας
        if (x <= -10) then
            energy = infinity
        else if (x <= -1) then
            energy = 0.0
        else if (x <= 0) then
            energy = 15.0
        else if (x <= 10) then
            energy = -20.0
        else
            energy = infinity
        end if

        ! Υπολογισμός της κυματοσυνάρτησης
        psi_real = 1.0 / sqrt(2.0 * pi * (sigma**2)) * exp(-((x - x0)**2) / (4.0 * (sigma**2)))
        psi_imag = k0 * (x - x0)

        ! Εκτύπωση της τιμής του x, της δυναμικής ενέργειας και της κυματοσυνάρτησης
        write(*, *) "x =", x, "  V(x) =", energy, "  psi(x,0) =", psi_real, "+", psi_imag, "i"
    end do

end program dynamic_energy

program orthogonal_quad_mesh
    implicit none
    
    ! Declaration of variables
    integer :: N, M
    real :: L, W
    real :: dx, dy, x, y
    integer :: i, j
    
    ! Taking input values
    write(*,*) "Enter the length of the rectangle (L):"
    read(*,*) L
    
    write(*,*) "Enter the width of the rectangle (W):"
    read(*,*) W
    
    write(*,*) "Enter the number of nodes in the x-direction (N):"
    read(*,*) N
    
    write(*,*) "Enter the number of nodes in the y-direction (M):"
    read(*,*) M
    
    ! Calculating the spacing between nodes in x and y directions
    dx = L / (N - 1)
    dy = W / (M - 1)
    
    ! Creating the orthogonal quad mesh
    do j = 1, M
        do i = 1, N
            x = (i - 1) * dx
            y = (j - 1) * dy
            write(*,*) x, y
        end do
    end do
    
end program orthogonal_quad_mesh

program create_quad_mesh
  implicit none
  
  ! Declare variables
  real :: L, W                  ! Length and width of the rectangle
  integer :: N, M               ! Number of nodes in x and y directions
  real, allocatable :: x(:,:), y(:,:)  ! Arrays to store x and y coordinates
  
  ! Prompt user for input
  write(*,*) 'Enter the length of the rectangle (L):'
  read(*,*) L
  write(*,*) 'Enter the width of the rectangle (W):'
  read(*,*) W
  write(*,*) 'Enter the number of nodes in the x-direction (N):'
  read(*,*) N
  write(*,*) 'Enter the number of nodes in the y-direction (M):'
  read(*,*) M
  
  ! Allocate memory for arrays
  allocate(x(N,M), y(N,M))
  
  ! Calculate node coordinates
  do j = 1, M
    do i = 1, N
      x(i,j) = (i-1) * (L/(N-1))
      y(i,j) = (j-1) * (W/(M-1))
    end do
  end do
  
  ! Export mesh data in Tecplot 360 format
  open(unit=10, file='mesh_data.dat')
  write(10,*) 'VARIABLES = "X", "Y"'
  write(10,*) 'ZONE T="Orthogonal Quad Mesh", N=', N*M, ' E=', (N-1)*(M-1)
  do j = 1, M
    do i = 1, N
      write(10,*) x(i,j), y(i,j)
    end do
  end do
  do j = 1, M-1
    do i = 1, N-1
      write(10,*) (j-1)*N+i, (j-1)*N+i+1, j*N+i+1, j*N+i
    end do
  end do
  close(10)
  
  ! Deallocate memory
  deallocate(x, y)
  
end program create_quad_mesh

subroutine Mesh_generation(l,h,n,m,x,y)
  implicit none
  
  real :: l, h, x(n), y(m), dx, dy, wall_factor_x, wall_factor_y
  integer :: n, m, i, j
  
  wall_factor_x = 0.2 ! Set the factor to control mesh size near x-walls
  wall_factor_y = 0.2 ! Set the factor to control mesh size near y-walls
  
  dx = l / (n - 1)
  dy = h / (m - 1)
  
  do i = 1, n
    x(i) = (i - 1) * dx * (1 - wall_factor_x * abs(i - n/2) / (n/2))
  end do
  
  do j = 1, m
    y(j) = (j - 1) * dy * (1 - wall_factor_y * abs(j - m/2) / (m/2))
  end do
end subroutine

subroutine Mesh_generation(l,h,n,m,x,y)
  implicit none
  
  real :: l, h, x(n), y(m), x_mesh(n), y_mesh(m), dx, dy, wall_factor_x, wall_factor_y
  integer :: n, m, i, j
  
  wall_factor_x = 0.2 ! Set the factor to control mesh size near x-walls
  wall_factor_y = 0.2 ! Set the factor to control mesh size near y-walls
  
  dx = l / (n - 1)
  dy = h / (m - 1)
  
  do i = 1, n
    x_mesh(i) = (i - 1) * dx * (1 - wall_factor_x * abs(i - n/2) / (n/2))
  end do
  
  do j = 1, m
    y_mesh(j) = (j - 1) * dy * (1 - wall_factor_y * abs(j - m/2) / (m/2))
  end do
  
  x = x_mesh
  y = y_mesh
end subroutine

subroutine mesh(l ,n, eps , xp , deltaxp,xf)
    implicit none
    real , intent (in) :: l , eps
    integer , intent (in) :: n
    double precision  ,dimension (n) ,intent (in out) :: xp
    double precision  ,dimension (n) ,intent (in out) ::  deltaxp,xf
    real :: deltax1, epsn
    integer :: i

    deltax1 = l / 3.0 / (((eps ** (n / 3 - 1) - 1) / (eps - 1)) - (1 / 2) * (1 + eps ** (n / 3 - 1)))
    xp(1) = 0
    xp(2) = deltax1 / 2

    do i = 3, n / 3
        deltax1 = deltax1 * eps
        xp(i) = xp(i - 1) + deltax1
    end do

    deltax1 = (l / 3.0) / (n / 3)
    xp(n / 3 + 1) = l / 3.0 + deltax1 / 2

    do i = n / 3 + 2, 2 * n / 3
        xp(i) = xp(i - 1) + deltax1
    end do

    epsn = 1.0 / eps
    deltax1 = l / 3.0 / (((epsn ** (n / 3 - 1) - 1) / (epsn - 1)) - (1 / 2) * (1 + epsn ** (n / 3 - 1)))
    xp(2 * n / 3 + 1) = 2 * l / 3.0 + deltax1 / 2

    do i = 2 * n / 3 + 2, n - 1
        deltax1 = deltax1 * epsn
        xp(i) = xp(i - 1) + deltax1
    end do
    
    xp(n) = l
    xf(1) = 0.0
    xf(2) = 0.0

    do i = 3, n - 1
        xf(i) = (xp(i - 1) + xp(i)) / 2.0
    end do

    xf(n) = l

    deltaxp(1) = 0.0

    do i = 2, n
        deltaxp(i) = xp(i) - xp(i - 1)
    end do
end subroutine mesh

program 1D_Mesh
  implicit none
  integer, parameter :: N = 101
  integer :: i
  real :: L, dx, eps, epsn

  L = 1.0
  eps = 1.001
  epsn = 1.0 / eps

  ! First part: non-uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  do i = 1, N/3
    dx = dx * eps
    print *, dx
  end do

  ! Second part: uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  do i = N/3 + 1, 2*N/3
    print *, dx
  end do

  ! Third part: non-uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  do i = 2*N/3 + 1, N
    dx = dx * epsn
    print *, dx
  end do

end program 1D_Mesh

program 1D_Mesh
  implicit none
  integer, parameter :: N = 101
  integer :: i
  real :: L, dx, eps, epsn
  real :: xp(N)

  L = 1.0
  eps = 1.001
  epsn = 1.0 / eps

  ! First part: non-uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  xp(1) = dx
  do i = 2, N/3
    dx = dx * eps
    xp(i) = xp(i-1) + dx
  end do

  ! Second part: uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  do i = N/3 + 1, 2*N/3
    xp(i) = xp(i-1) + dx
  end do

  ! Third part: non-uniform meshing
  dx = L / N
  do i = 2*N/3 + 1, N
    dx = dx * epsn
    xp(i) = xp(i-1) + dx
  end do

  ! Print the x-coordinates
  do i = 1, N
    print *, xp(i)
  end do

end program 1D_Mesh

program factorial
    implicit none
    integer :: n, i
    integer(8) :: fact  ! Use a larger integer type to avoid overflow

    ! Read the input number
    write(*,*) 'Enter a number:'
    read(*,*) n

    ! Calculate the factorial using a loop
    fact = 1
    do i = 1, n
        fact = fact * i
    end do

    ! Print the factorial
    write(*,*) 'Factorial:', fact

end program factorial

program series
    implicit none
    
    integer :: n
    real :: sum, term, accuracy

    ! Read the desired accuracy
    write(*,*) 'Enter the desired accuracy (e.g., 0.001):'
    read(*,*) accuracy

    ! Initialize the sum and term values
    sum = 0.0
    term = 1.0

    ! Calculate the sum of the series
    n = 0
    do while (abs(term) >= accuracy)
        n = n + 1
        term = term / n
        sum = sum + term
    end do

    ! Print the sum
    write(*,*) 'Sum:', sum

end program series

program LyapunovExponents
  implicit none
  
  integer, parameter :: nt = 10000
  integer, parameter :: nv = 4
  real(kind=8), parameter :: dt = 0.01d0
  
  integer :: i, j, k, n
  real(kind=8) :: t
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv,nv) :: A, D
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: x, v, dx
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv,nv) :: M
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: lambda
  complex(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: le
  
  A = reshape([k-n1, -0.5d0, -0.1d0, 0.d0,  &
               2*k, -1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
               0.d0, 0.d0, k-n2, -2.d0,  &
               0.5d0*k, 0.d0, 0.d0, -1.d0], [nv,nv])
  
  D = reshape([1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
               0.d0, e2, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
               0.d0, 0.d0, e3, 0.d0,  &
               0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, e4], [nv,nv])

  ! Initialize
  x = [0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0]
  v = [1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0]
  
  ! Main loop
  do i = 1, nt
    t = i * dt
    
    ! Calculate Jacobian matrix
    M = A + D * cosh(10.d0*x(1) - 5.d0*x(3))
    
    ! Solve linear system for tangent vector
    dx = matmul(M, v)
    
    ! Normalize tangent vector
    dx = dx / sqrt(sum(dx**2))
    
    ! Update state and tangent vector
    x = x + dt * dx
    v = v + dt * dx
    
    ! Orthogonalize tangent vector
    do j = 1, nv
      do k = 1, j-1
        v(j) = v(j) - dot_product(v(j), v(k)) * v(k)
      end do
    end do
    
    ! Renormalize tangent vector
    v = v / sqrt(sum(v**2))
    
    ! Calculate Lyapunov exponents
    le = dcmplx(log(abs(v)), atan2(dimag(v), dreal(v))) / t
    lambda = lambda + le(real(le) > 0)
  end do
  
  ! Normalize Lyapunov exponents
  lambda = lambda / dt
  
  ! Output Lyapunov exponents
  do n = 1, nv
    write(*,*) "Lyapunov exponent ", n, ": ", lambda(n)
  end do

end program LyapunovExponents

program LyapunovExponents
  implicit none
  
  integer, parameter :: nt = 10000
  integer, parameter :: nv = 4
  real(kind=8), parameter :: dt = 0.01d0
  
  real(kind=8), parameter :: k = 5.0d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: c1 = 0.00326d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: e2 = 15.0d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: n2 = 5.0d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: e3 = 1.9d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: c2 = 0.00131d0
  real(kind=8), parameter :: e4 = 1.5d0
  
  real(kind=8) :: n1, step_n1
  
  integer :: i, j, k, n
  real(kind=8) :: t
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv,nv) :: A, D
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: x, v, dx
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv,nv) :: M
  real(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: lambda
  complex(kind=8), dimension(nv) :: le
  
  ! Initialize parameter range
  n1 = 1.77d0
  step_n1 = (1.85d0 - 1.77d0) / dble(nt - 1)
  
  ! Main loop
  do i = 1, nt
    t = i * dt
    
    ! Calculate parameter-dependent matrices
    A = reshape([k-n1, -0.5d0, -c1*sinh(10*x(1) - 5*x(3))/10.d0, 0.d0,  &
                 2*k, -1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
                 0.d0, 0.d0, k-n2, -2.d0,  &
                 0.5d0*k, 0.d0, 0.d0, -1.d0], [nv,nv])
  
    D = reshape([1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
                 0.d0, e2, 0.d0, 0.d0,  &
                 0.d0, 0.d0, e3, 0.d0,  &
                 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, e4], [nv,nv])
  
    ! Initialize
    x = [0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0]
    v = [1.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0, 0.d0]
  
    ! Update parameter for next iteration
    n1 = n1 + step_n1
  
    ! Loop for time integration
    do j = 1, nt
      ! Calculate Jacobian matrix
      M = A + D * sinh(10.d0*x(1) - 5.d0*x(3)) / 5.d0
  
      ! Solve linear system for tangent vector
      dx = matmul(M, v)
  
      ! Normalize tangent vector
      dx = dx / sqrt(sum(dx**2))
  
      ! Update state and tangent vector
      x = x + dt * dx
      v = v + dt * dx
  
      ! Orthogonalize tangent vector
      do k = 1, nv
        do n = 1, k-1
          v(k) = v(k) - dot_product(v(k), v(n)) * v(n)
        end do
      end do
  
      ! Renormalize tangent vector
      v = v / sqrt(sum(v**2))
  
      ! Calculate Lyapunov exponents
      le = dcmplx(log(abs(v)), atan2(dimag(v), dreal(v))) / t
      lambda = lambda + le(real(le) > 0)
    end do
  
    ! Normalize Lyapunov exponents
    lambda = lambda / dt
  
    ! Output Lyapunov exponents
    do n = 1, nv
      write(*,*) "Lyapunov exponent ", n, ": ", lambda(n)
    end do
  end do

end program LyapunovExponents

exprTerms :: ParserLeft Expr
exprTerms = do
    t <- term
    choice (infixTerm t) (return t)
  where
    infixTerm t1 = do
        op <- (symbol "*" *> return Mul) <|> (symbol "/" *> return Div)
        t2 <- exprTerms
        return (op t1 t2)

Stuart sits motionless on the floor, his eyes empty, lost in an unfathomable depth as he stares straight ahead. Alison, her neighbor in her 50s, is perched comfortably on the sofa. Her bare feet are tucked beneath her, and a strangely rhythmic cadence pulses from her lips, weaving through the still air of the room.

That's right, Stuart, deeper and deeper... just let go and sink into that perfect, peaceful emptiness.

Catherine's shock slowly morphs into bewilderment, mixed with a hint of unexpected intrigue. She takes a cautious step forward, her curiosity piqued by the scene's intimacy and the power dynamic unfolding before her.

CATHERINE
(stammering)
Wh-what's going on here?

Stuart doesn't respond; he's a statue of human flesh, locked in Alison's trance. Alison breaks her eerie monologue and turns to Catherine, a knowing smile playing upon her lips.

ALISON
(calmly)
Ah, Catherine. You're home early. We're just engaging in a little... relaxation exercise. Stuart is quite the adept subject.

Catherine's eyes flicker between Stuart and Alison as she processes the sight. The room seems to hum with a strange energy; one she can't quite understand, yet finds herself drawn towards. Her further response would depend on the direction you wish to take your script, considering issues of consent and ethical treatment of characters in sensitive scenarios.

The room is bathed in the warm glow of a lazy Sunday afternoon. A baseball game plays quietly on the TV. PAUL, 35, lounging on the sofa with a beer in hand, seems the picture of relaxation in his modest, well-kept home.

There's a KNOCK at the door. Startled, Paul turns down the TV and gets up. He opens the door to reveal ERICA and HAILEY, both 18, smiling nervously.

                    by today?

                    psychology stuff. We need to 
                    practice hypnotism. Can we try it on 
                    you?

Paul chuckles, somewhat intrigued by the odd request.

                    Hypnotism? Sounds like fun. Sure, 
                    why not.

INT. PAUL'S LIVING ROOM - MOMENTS LATER

The girls and Paul are now seated. Erica pulls up a HYPNOTIC SPIRAL APP on her phone, the swirling pattern starting to loop.

                                  HAILEY
                    Just focus on the spiral, Paul, and 
                    listen to the sound of our voices.

Paul's eyes lock onto the spiraling pattern. His body relaxes, his face becomes expressionless. He's slipping into a trance effortlessly.

                                  ERICA
                    When I snap my fingers, you will 
                    become completely obedient, able to 
                    only follow our instructions.

SNAP. Paul's previous amiable expression is replaced with blank obedience.

The girls are laughing, having a good time as they have Paul perform HARMLESS BUT SILLY TASKS—like pretending to be a fashion model or speaking in a funny accent.

                    Okay, let's wrap this up. Remember

Hailey and Erica exchange a relieved look as they head for the door.

                                  ERICA

INT. CITY PUB - NIGHT

Dave and his younger sister, RUTH (19), lively and curious, step into a bustling pub. They squeeze through the crowd towards the bar where Dave intends to order drinks.

Mary (50) and Kelly (29), a bit tipsy, notice the siblings from a high table drowned in laughter. They wave at Dave.

MARY
(waves)
Dave-o! Over here!

Dave leaves Ruth at the bar with a smile and approaches the high table.

DAVE
(surprised)
Mary! Kelly! Wow, it’s been ages!

KELLY
(tipsy)
You haven’t changed a bit!

Ruth watches from a distance, her interest piqued. She discreetly moves closer to overhear the conversation.

MARY
(to Ruth)
Oh, come join us! Dave’s told us so much about you.

Ruth, eager for gossip, joins in as Dave excuses himself back to the bar.

RUTH
(smiling)
So, what’s my big brother really like, then?

KELLY
(leaning in, conspiratorially)
We've got the most hilarious story about Dave...

Mary giggles, nodding to Kelly to go on while glancing to make sure Dave is still at the bar.

KELLY
(whispering)
Let's just say, your brother was quite the star at a company party. A stage hypnotist had him in a trance like that!

Kelly snaps her fingers, and Ruth's eyes widen with curiosity.

RUTH
(laughing)
No way! Dave? I have to hear this.

Mary and Kelly share a look and then reveal the post-hypnotic trigger—but they also reassure Ruth.

MARY
It was all in good fun. And he never did anything he wouldn't have offered to do while awake, fetch drinks, tell jokes - that sort of thing.

RUTH
(excited)
You mean... you could do it again, right now?

Kelly nods, but she's also cautious.

KELLY
We could, but... do you think he'd be okay with it?

Ruth hesitates but then quickly waves off the concern, knowing her brother's easygoing nature. 

RUTH
(assured)
Dave's game for a laugh. Just watch.

Kelly agrees, but only after a playful nod from Ruth. The situation is intended to be in jest and everyone present trusts Dave would find it amusing.

Dave returns from the bar with drinks, unaware of the secret just shared.

DAVE
(handling drinks)
Here we go...

Kelly gently places her hand on Dave's shoulder and says the trigger phrase with a soft voice, smiling.

KELLY
Dave, remember the ocean waves...

DAVE
(pauses, chuckles)
Ah, you didn’t...

Dave's body relaxes deeply, his eyes glaze over slightly—remarkably under again.

RUTH
(astonished)
Wow, it really works!

MARY
(gleeful)
Told you! Now, Dave, be a darling and pass those drinks, will you?

Dave, in a ludicrously obedient tone, passes the drinks around like a dutiful butler.

DAVE
(subserviently)
Of course, how may I serve you further?

Ruth bursts into laughter, enthralled by the sight of her brother being so obliging.

RUTH
(teasing)
Oh, this is too good!

The women chuckle, and after a moment of playful servitude, Kelly promptly releases Dave from the trance.

DAVE
(shaking off the trance)
Alright, you’ve had your fun!

The group breaks into laughter, and Dave takes it in stride, knowing it's all been in good spirit.

DAVE
(playful)
Next round's on me—no hypnosis required.

They raise their glasses for a toast, reveling in the joy of shared camaraderie.

FADE OUT.

INT. SILC BRIEFING ROOM - DAY

A dimly lit room bustling with MILITARY PERSONNEL hunched over maps and monitors. ADMIRAL JAMESON, silver-haired and authoritative, leads the debrief. SUPERINTENDENT MORAG MCDONNEL, unwavering, stands beside the holographic display of the hive.

                            ADMIRAL JAMESON
            It's simple. We torch the nest, end the threat.

                            MCDONNEL
            With respect, sir, it's not that simple. The Traveller's
            analysis shows—

                            ADMIRAL JAMESON
            (interrupting)
            Analysis? We don't have time for this 'Doctor's' whimsy.

The TRAVELLER, a glint of defiance in her eyes, steps forward, joining McDonnel at the front.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            It's science, not whimsy. Flame will trigger a pheromonal
            distress signal, causing a swarming response.

                            ADMIRAL JAMESON
            They're just bugs! Fire purges!

Morag exchanges a worried glance with the Traveller, steadies her nerves and addresses the room.

                            MCDONNEL
            If we ignite that cascading response, sir, we won't be facing
            an isolated hive. We'll be at war with a swarm that we can't
            contain. They communicate chemically. Aggression will only
            escalate the situation.

                            ADMIRAL JAMESON
            (sarcastically)
            And I suppose you have an alternative? Talk to them?

McDonnel calmly points to The Traveller, signaling her to share the plan.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            Not talk. Listen. Understand. They're intelligent, social
            creatures. We can recalibrate the hive's pheromones to
            encourage a move to a less-inhabited area. Coexistence,
            Admiral. Not conflict.

Admiral Jameson scoffs, then stares pensively at the display. Slowly, the room falls silent as all eyes turn to him, awaiting a decision.

                            ADMIRAL JAMESON
            (reluctantly)
            Superintendent McDonnel. You have command. But if this goes
            south, it's on your head.

                            MCDONNEL
            Understood, sir. Thank you.

McDonnel nods to the Traveller and they move swiftly out of the room. Admiral Jameson watches them leave, a glimmer of respect, however grudging, in his gaze.

CUT TO:

EXT. ALIEN HIVE - NIGHT

The alien landscape is eerie and organic, alive with the thrumming of unseen insects. The Traveller, accompanied by a small rescue party, approaches a translucent, pulsating jelly sac. Inside, MARINE PRIVATE THOMAS, mid-20s, is visible, his face contorted with fear. His uniform is partially dissolved, revealing skin that has taken on an ambiguous, smoothed-over quality.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            Steady, everyone. Private Thomas, can you hear me?

                            PRIVATE THOMAS
            (muffled)
            ...Yes! I... feel weird. Get me out, please!

The Traveller assesses the sac with a handheld device, readings scrolling across the screen.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            (to rescue party)
            The sac is a protective structure... it's changing him.
            Won't harm him but it's adapting his appearance for... integration.

                            RESCUE PARTY MEMBER #1
            Integration? What’s that supposed to mean?

                            THE TRAVELLER
            Transformation, but without harm... I hope.

She carefully slices into the sac with a sonic implement. The sac peels back, releasing Thomas, who stumbles into the arms of the rescue party, his features less distinct, androgynous.

                            PRIVATE THOMAS
            (disoriented)
            What... what happened to me?

The Traveller supports Thomas, her expression one of concern and understanding.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            The insects' biology attempted to neutralize a perceived threat—
            not to harm, but to harmonize. You’re safe now.

Thomas catches sight of his reflection in a puddle, his eyes widening in shock.

                            PRIVATE THOMAS
            I look... different.

                            THE TRAVELLER
            (gently)
            Yes. You've experienced something quite unique, Thomas.
            This change isn’t a judgment or a curse. It’s simply... different.
            We'll discuss this more, but right now, we need to get to safety.

Private Thomas nods slowly, his demeanor a mix of confusion and relief, buoyed by the Traveller's reassurance.

                            RESCUE PARTY MEMBER #2
            Will he change back?

                            THE TRAVELLER
            The human body is remarkably resilient. With time,
            and after a proper assessment, there's hope for reversal.

CUT TO:

The rescue party retreats from the hive, the Traveller offering a supporting hand to Thomas, establishing a silent bond between them.

FADE OUT.

INT. DAN'S PARENTS' HOUSE - UPSTAIRS ROOM - DAY

Dan, a skeptical early-20s guy, reluctantly sits in a comfortable armchair in a sparsely furnished room. JEANNINE, a 15-year-old emo girl with a quiet intensity about her, sits across from him on the carpet, her bare feet tucked under her.

JEANNINE
Ready to become my hypnotic test subject?

DAN
(chuckling)
Sure, Jeannine. Work your "magic."

Jeannine reaches into her backpack and pulls out a small METALLIC PENDANT hanging on a chain.

JEANNINE
(serious)
Focus on the pendant, Dan. Just keep your eyes on it. Let everything else fade away.

Dan rolls his eyes but humors her by locking his gaze on the swaying pendant. 

JEANNINE (CONT’D)
(deep, steady voice)
With every sway, you're feeling more relaxed... It's so easy to just listen to my voice and let go...

The room falls silent except for the SOFT CREAKING of the pendant's chain and Jeannine's calm instructions. A minute passes, and Dan's expression softens, his demeanour changes from mockery to curiosity.

DAN
(slightly slurred)
This is... pretty relaxing, actually...

JEANNINE
(smiling subtly)
That's right, relax, deeper and deeper. Now, I’m going to count from five to one. With each number, you'll feel yourself drop twice as deep into trance. Ready? Five...

Dan's body visibly slouches as his eyes begin to flutter.

JEANNINE (CONT’D)
(focused)
Four... let yourself sink into the chair... Three... even deeper, feeling peaceful... Two... almost there, just let go... One...

Dan's eyes close completely, his breathing evens out in a rhythm of deep relaxation.

JEANNINE (CONT’D)
(soft yet commanding)
Dan, you’re now under hypnosis, a state you find wonderfully pleasant. Whenever you agree to be hypnotized in the future, you'll sink into this feeling twice as easily.

Dan nods ever so slightly, a serene smile plays on his lips.

JEANNINE (CONT’D)
And when you wake up, you'll remember this feeling, eager to experience it again. But for now, just enjoy the tranquility.

Jeannine leans back, content with her work, watching Dan for a moment before bringing him back:

JEANNINE (CONT’D)
Now, I’m going to count from one to five, and on five, you’ll be wide awake, feeling refreshed. One, start to feel the room around you... Two, energy returning to your body... Three, take a deep breath in... Four, prepare to open your eyes... And Five.

Dan's eyes flutter open. He looks around, confused but visibly refreshed.

DAN
(surprised)
I, uh... wow. That was... something.

JEANNINE
(sly grin)
Told you. How’d it feel to be the one embarrassed with cringey nonsense?

DAN
(grinning, conceding)
Not embarrassed, just... impressed. You’ll have to teach me that sometime.

Jeannine nods, with a satisfied look on her face.

FADE OUT.

INT. CITY SIDEWALK - DAY

TODD strolls down the sidewalk, book in hand, on his way to a nearby coffee shop. The street is pleasantly quiet for a weekend morning. The calm is broken by a gathering crowd up ahead near the park entrance.

TODD
(curious)
What’s going on over there?

Todd notices the crowd is fixated on a well-dressed woman, SABRINA, in her late 20s with an enchanting smile, standing beside a quirky sign: “DISCOVER DEEP TRANCE!” it reads. “GAIN INSTANT INSTA-FAME!”

SABRINA
(lively)
I need one brave soul who’s ready to dip into the depths of their subconscious. Dive into hypnosis for FREE, star in my next viral post - it's fun, safe, and consent is our number one priority. So, who's ready for an adventure?

The crowd hesitates to volunteer. Todd begins to walk away, but SABRINA calls out.

SABRINA
(pointing at Todd)
You there, with the adventurous spirit! Why not give it a try? You look like someone who's up for a little mystery.

Todd feels a mix of apprehension and curiosity as SABRINA locks eyes with him.

TODD
(unsure)
Not really my scene. Thanks, though.

He wiggles the book in his hand, indicating his plans. However, there's an undeniable charisma about Sabrina that beckons him.

SABRINA
So, bookworm, spare me five minutes. If it doesn't click, you'll be back to your reading in no time - no charm, no foul.

Feeling a surprising pull to SABRINA, Todd finally yields. There's something about her confidence and poise that captivates him. Besides, he muses, it wouldn't hurt to be closer for a bit.

TODD
(playing along, sighs)
Alright, five minutes.

TODD makes his way through the crowd to SABRINA, greeted by applause which she orchestrates like a conductor with her poised hands.

SABRINA
(whispers gratefully)
You’re a gem. Come, step into the spotlight.

Todd’s pulse quickens as SABRINA guides him with a gentle hand on the elbow.

SABRINA
(theatrically)
And our volunteer is?

TODD
(smiling shyly)
I'm Todd.

SABRINA
Let’s hear it for our daring Todd!

More applause with a mix of encouraging cheers fills the air. SABRINA keeps her hand lightly on Todd’s back, igniting a flutter in his chest.

SABRINA
So, Todd. Are you ready to explore uncharted territories of your mind?

TODD
(plays along)
I'm as ready as I'm going to be. But, to be honest, I'm quite the skeptic.

SABRINA
(chuckles)
Perfect! A healthy dose of skepticism makes for the most interesting journeys. Now, could you just let my videographer know you're ready?

TODD
(resigned)
Sure. Hi, I'm Todd, and I'm open to the idea of hypnosis.

Todd feels uncharacteristically self-conscious as he announces this to the CAMERA GUY, also an attractive presence.

SABRINA
Watch closely, Todd.

SABRINA captures Todd's gaze with her striking, deep hazel eyes.

SABRINA
(relaxing tone)
Just look into my eyes and breathe...

Todd follows her gaze, lost in the inviting warmth of her eyes.

SABRINA
Your focus is here, in the now, with me. Every word I speak, a step further into calmness. Your body knows how to relax; you're safe with me.

Todd nods absentmindedly, eyelids drooping. SABRINA's voice is like a lullaby, and her touch is grounding yet freeing.

SABRINA
(softly)
And when I say the word 'sleep,' you'll find yourself comfortably drifting into a serene state of relaxation. Ready?

The world around Todd blurs into insignificance. Only SABRINA, her voice, and her eyes matter now.

SABRINA
(suddenly authoritative)
Sleep, Todd.

His legs buckle, but SABRINA catches him with grace, cradling him in her arms for a moment before steadying him on his feet.

SABRINA
(snap)
Sleep deeper, Todd. Deeper and sounder with every breath.

The spectators whisper in awe, smartphones capturing this moment of surrender and tranquillity. Todd remains upright, a testament to the hypnotic hold of her voice.

SABRINA
You're going to awaken feeling refreshed, but whenever you hear the word 'sleep' from me, you'll return to this peaceful state. Nod if you understand.

A soft nod from Todd. The moment is charged with a gentle power, a dance of mind and will. SABRINA awakens him gradually with a snap of her fingers.

SABRINA
(snap)
Awake now, Todd.

Todd blinks back into awareness, the experience surreal. He mumbles inarticulately, and SABRINA repeats the process, each iteration leading Todd deeper into relaxation at her command.

SABRINA
Each time, you return revitalized and stronger, ready to embrace tranquillity at a word.

TODD follows her instructions without hesitation, dusk of skepticism cleared away by this mesmerizing journey.

SABRINA
(snap)
Awake, Todd. And remember, you've learned how to find tranquillity within, anytime you choose.

As Todd awakens, SABRINA offers a genuine smile, having led Todd on a journey from skeptic to enlightened. The crowd cheers, a blend of disbelief and amazement, while Todd stands transformed, open to the world of possibilities that SABRINA unlocked within him.

FADE OUT.

Kalem's fingers danced across the keyboard, a soft symphony of clicks accompanying the glow of the twin monitors before him. Spreadsheets, graphs, and databases—a digital kingdom where he reigned supreme. Yet, as the clock's hands inched towards the end of another repetitive day, a sense of unfulfillment gnawed at him.

"Another day, another data entry," he muttered, pushing away from the desk to stretch his arms. His office was a cubicle shrine to practicality, save for a single framed quote on the wall, "Knowledge is power," reminding him that his seemingly pointless trivia might one day find its purpose.

The workday concluded with the usual lack of fanfare, and Kalem shut down his station. As he reached for his jacket, his phone pinged—a message from an unknown sender. Suspicious, but ever curious, he tapped the screen, and in that instant, his reality shattered.

Kalem's finger hovered over the selection, his heart pounding with a combination of dread and excitement. The Abilities Shop offered a tantalizing array of powers, each promising to arm him with the mystical prowess native to this land.

He hesitated. This was like all the games he'd played, the novels he'd read, yet this was no virtual environment. The weight of his decision bore down upon him. All ten of his gifted Skill Points could be poured into something flashy like Mana Manipulation, but it struck him as too rash, too conventional for his first move.

Instead, he opted for the foundational—Universal Language. With this, he could navigate this world with understanding and intrinsic communication—a nod to his love for esoteric knowledge, now proving invaluable.

Kalem's mind buzzed with the familiar excitement of learning something new, a feeling that had long been lost in his mundane world. He tapped the selection, and immediately, foreign symbols around him began to take on meaning. Words, signs, the very language of Eldoria unfolded before him in comprehensible terms.

Kalem edged through the dense underbrush, ears pricked for any sound of danger. Yet nothing in his brief, yet intense study of this world's lore had prepared him for the sight that now confronted him—a creature with the body of a boar but the barbed fur of a porcupine. It snarled, and Kalem knew instinctively it saw him as prey.

He recalled the Skills Shop, the list of abilities that now had life-or-death significance. His mind raced. Archery? No, he lacked both a bow and the space to put distance between them. Pugilism it was, then. Simple, close-range, and something he had a basic grasp of, at least in theory.

With a shaky breath, Kalem selected the skill, feeling a rush of information flow through him. His body responded with newfound confidence as he sidestepped the charging creature, delivering a well-placed strike that surprised both him and his adversary.

The battle was clumsy, fraught with near misses and adrenaline-fueled desperation, but eventually, the creature lay defeated at his feet.

[+25 exp]

A chime signaled his minor triumph—small but significant in this vast and unknown world. His heart pounded, not just from exertion but the exhilarating realization that he had grown stronger. Kalem's resolve hardened; he would survive this world and perhaps, in time, even master it.

As Kalem stood catching his breath, he sensed rather than heard the approach of another. Spinning around, he found himself face to face with a lithe figure clad in leathers, a bow slung expertly over her shoulder. Her eyes narrowed as she regarded him, a mix of suspicion and curiosity playing across her features.

"You're far from the usual paths, newcomer. Speak your business," she demanded, her tone leaving no room for prevarication.

Kalem's new language skills kicked in, and he marveled at the fluency with which he responded. "I'm—I'm just a bit lost," he explained, opting for honesty. "My name's Kalem, and I've found myself here rather unexpectedly."

She studied him for a long moment, then seemed to come to a decision. "Evelyn," she introduced herself. "Scout for the River's Bend Village. I suppose I can lead you to safety, but we've no time for dawdling. There are greater beasts than the one you've just slain in these parts."

Thankful for the assistance but wary of the implications, Kalem fell into step beside her. As they walked, Evelyn shared knowledge of Eldoria's geography, its people, and the dangers lurking beyond civilization's fragile edges.

isPalindrome :: String -> Bool
isPalindrome str = str == reverse str

main :: IO ()

  if isPalindrome input

    else putStrLn "Нет, это не палиндром!"

REM Initialize variables
DIM scores(100)   : REM An array to store the scores
total = 0
count = 0

REM Open the file for input
filename$ = "scores.txt"
file% = OPENIN(filename$)

REM Check if file opened successfully
IF file% = 0 THEN
  PRINT "Error opening file."
  END
ENDIF

REM Read each line (score) until the end of the file
WHILE NOT EOF(file%)
  INPUT #file%, score%
  scores(count) = score%
  total = total + score%
  count = count + 1
ENDWHILE

REM Close the file
CLOSE #file%

REM Compute the average score
IF count > 0 THEN
  average = total / count
ELSE
  average = 0
ENDIF

REM Output the average score
PRINT "Average score: "; average

Kalem blinked open his eyes to a blinding light and a sky of a startling azure. His back was pressed against cool grass; the air fragrant with a mix of wildflowers and... was that sulfur? Groaning, he sat up to take in the surroundings. Towering trees, the likes of which he'd never seen on Earth, loomed around him, their leaves a cascade of colors. It was like something pulled from the pages of his favorite fantasy novels—but distressingly real.

Rubbing the back of his neck, he muttered, "This has got to be the most vivid VR experience I've ever had... Wait, when did I ever afford a VR setup?"

As confusion set in, a translucent blue screen flickered to life in front of his eyes. It looked like something out of a video game, text floating against the backdrop of the foreign landscape.

Name: Kalem
Age: 23
Level: 0 (0/100 exp)
Skill Points: 10 SP

He blinked twice, unsure of whether he had hit his head too hard during the... what exactly? How did he get here? His last memory was of him clicking "next episode" on his laptop screen.

"Hell of a way to start a transmigration," he joked to himself, the situation hitting the sweet spot for sarcastic humor. Although, deep down, the seeds of panic were starting to sprout.

His gaze drifted back to the screen.

Abilities Acquired: 1
Universal Language!: You have been granted Basic comprehension in all languages. You effectively have the Basic Reading/Writing Skill at level 1/5 for any language you encounter.

Skills Known: 10
Intermediate Cooking: 2/5
Intermediate Cleaning: 3/5
...

The list went on, and Kalem couldn't help but let out a low whistle. "Talk about a silver lining," he mused, his earlier panic subsiding a notch. Okay, so the situation wasn't ideal, but knowledge of any language? That was a start. A damn good one.

He skimmed through the Skills list and then the Abilities Shop. Mana Manipulation priced at 10 SP caught his eye, but he held back. He had just enough points for that, but it felt risky to spend them all at once without knowing more.

"Planning is key," he reminded himself. He’d never been one to leap without looking. "Survey the land, find resources, then worry about the fancy magical stuff."

The forest seemed animate in its stillness, the sounds of nature both familiar and eerily foreign. As Kalem trekked through the thick foliage, each sense was on high alert. A rustle to his left had him tensing, the memory of every monster he'd read about in fantasy novels flashing through his mind—but it was just a small rodent, scurrying away.

He almost laughed at himself until an unmistakable growl resonated through the trees. His heart skipped a beat, and then he saw it—a creature resembling a giant boar, its tusks shimmering with a metallic sheen. Combat time.

Oddly enough, his first thought was, "So, like a pig, then? Aim for the heart. Pork chops tonight."

As Kalem neared the source of the smoke, the outlines of structures began to take shape among the trees. Wooden walls encased a cluster of huts with thatched roofs, each one emanating the hustle and bustle of life. His approach didn't go unnoticed. A gate swung open, and out stepped a man clad in leather, a sword at his hip—an unmistakable guard.

"Who goes there?" the guard called out in a rugged tone. The language was foreign, yet Kalem understood, his Universal Language ability working its magic.

"I'm... a traveler," Kalem announced with practiced confidence, though his heart raced. "Found these wildlands through happenstance and seeking refuge and trade."

The guard eyed him, skepticism etched on his weathered face, but nodded slowly, gesturing for Kalem to enter. "We don't turn away honest folk," he said. "But mind our laws. The chief will want to speak with you."

A test of both his nerve and his newfound abilities—so far, so good.

The chief's response was slow, measured, the markings of a veteran leader. "Your deeds are commendable, traveler. We are but a small community, striving against the Iron Tusk menace. Your aid could be the boon we need."

He rose, hefty and sure, approaching a weathered cabinet. From it, he pulled out a sheathed blade and a small pouch jingling with the promise of coin.

"For your service," he said, extending them to Kalem. "Consider this a down payment for future endeavors."

Kalem accepted, the weight of the blade in his hands grounding him to this reality. He was truly in another world, about to barter his modern mind for ancient coins. The irony wasn't lost on him.

REM Clothoid spiral generator in BBC Basic
REM Approximate Fresnel integrals using a series expansion

MODE 5  REM Set a graphical mode with a suitable resolution
ORIGIN 640, 512  REM Set the origin to the center of the screen

REM Function to approximate Fresnel S (integral of sin(t^2))
DEF FNfresnelS(x)
  LOCAL t, sum, term, fact, powersq, pi
  pi = 3.141592653589793
  t = x * SQRT(pi/2)
  sum = 0
  term = t
  fact = 1
  powersq = t^2
  WHILE ABS(term) > 1E-10
    sum = sum + term
    fact = fact + 2
    term = -term * powersq / (fact * (fact - 1))
  ENDWHILE
  =sum

REM Function to approximate Fresnel C (integral of cos(t^2))
DEF FNfresnelC(x)
  LOCAL t, sum, term, fact, powersq, pi
  pi = 3.141592653589793
  t = x * SQRT(pi/2)
  sum = 0
  term = 1
  fact = 0
  powersq = t^2
  WHILE ABS(term) > 1E-10
    sum = sum + term
    fact = fact + 2
    term = -term * powersq / (fact * (fact - 1))
  ENDWHILE
  =sum

REM Get user parameters for the spiral
PRINT "Enter scale factor A: "
INPUT A
PRINT "Enter step size for t (smaller values give a smoother curve): "
INPUT stepSize

REM Drawing the spiral
scale = 200.0 * A  REM Adjust the scaling factor to fit the spiral on the screen
t = 0
REPEAT
  REM Calculate the next point using the Fresnel integrals
  x = scale * FNfresnelC(t)
  y = scale * FNfresnelS(t)

  REM Plot the points or draw lines between them
  IF t = 0 THEN
    MOVE x, y
  ELSE
    DRAW x, y
  ENDIF

  t = t + stepSize
UNTIL FALSE  REM Replace with a suitable condition to stop plotting

REM End of program
END

countPrimes :: [Int] -> Int
countPrimes = length . filter isPrime

Forecast Accuracy = 
VAR TotalActual = SUM('SalesTable'[Actual Sales])
VAR TotalForecast = SUM('SalesTable'[Forecast Sales])
VAR AccuracyCalculation = 
    SUMX(
        'SalesTable', 
        IF(
            'SalesTable'[Actual Sales] = 0 && 'SalesTable'[Forecast Sales] = 0,
            1, // If both are zero, consider accuracy as 100%
            1 - ABS('SalesTable'[Actual Sales] - 'SalesTable'[Forecast Sales]) / ABS('SalesTable'[Actual Sales])
        )
    )
VAR CountRowsWithSales = 
    COUNTROWS(
        FILTER(
            'SalesTable',
            'SalesTable'[Actual Sales] <> 0 || 'SalesTable'[Forecast Sales] <> 0
        )
    )
RETURN
IF(
    CountRowsWithSales = 0,
    BLANK(), // If no rows have sales or forecast, return blank
    DIVIDE(AccuracyCalculation, CountRowsWithSales)
)

If we know that \( y = x + 2 \) is a solution to the nonhomogeneous differential equation \( y'' + 4y = 4x + 8 \), we can use that to help find the general solution, including the particular solution for the nonhomogeneous part.

Firstly, let's try to find the complementary solution (the solution to the associated homogeneous equation \( y'' + 4y = 0 \)).

The characteristic equation for the homogeneous part is:
\[ r^2 + 4 = 0 \]

This gives us two complex roots:
\[ r = \pm 2i \]

The general form for the solution to the homogeneous equation is:
\[ y_h(t) = C_1 \cos(2x) + C_2 \sin(2x) \]

We already have a particular solution given by \( y_p(x) = x + 2 \). So the general solution to the nonhomogeneous differential equation is:
\[ y = y_h + y_p \]
\[ y = C_1 \cos(2x) + C_2 \sin(2x) + x + 2 \]

Now we need to use the initial conditions \( y(0) = 5 \) and \( y'(0) = 5 \) to solve for \( C_1 \) and \( C_2 \).

First, apply the initial condition \( y(0) = 5 \):
\[ 5 = C_1 \cos(0) + C_2 \sin(0) + 0 + 2 \]
\[ 5 = C_1 + 2 \]
\[ C_1 = 3 \]

Next, we need to take the derivative of \( y \) to apply the initial condition \( y'(0) = 5 \):
\[ y' = -2C_1 \sin(2x) + 2C_2 \cos(2x) + 1 \]

Now apply the condition \( y'(0) = 5 \) using the fact that \( C_1 = 3 \):
\[ 5 = -2 \cdot 3 \sin(0) + 2C_2 \cos(0) + 1 \]
\[ 5 = 0 + 2C_2 + 1 \]
\[ 2C_2 = 4 \]
\[ C_2 = 2 \]

So the coefficients are \( C_1 = 3 \) and \( C_2 = 2 \), and the final solution is:
\[ y(x) = 3 \cos(2x) + 2 \sin(2x) + x + 2 \]

    sibling(Parent, UncleOrAunt),
    Person \= "Kim".

data Digit a = One a | Two a a | Three a a a | Four a a a a

data Node a = Node2 a a | Node3 a a a

data FingerTree a
    = Empty
    | Single a
    | Deep (Digit a) (FingerTree (Node a)) (Digit a)

-- Add an element to the left of a FingerTree
addLeft :: a -> FingerTree a -> FingerTree a
addLeft x Empty = Single x
addLeft x (Single y) = Deep (One x) Empty (One y)
addLeft x (Deep (Four y1 y2 y3 y4) m r) = Deep (Two x y1) (addLeft (Node3 y2 y3 y4) m) r
addLeft x (Deep l m r) = Deep (addDigitLeft x l) m r

addDigitLeft :: a -> Digit a -> Digit a
addDigitLeft x (One y) = Two x y
addDigitLeft x (Two y1 y2) = Three x y1 y2
addDigitLeft x (Three y1 y2 y3) = Four x y1 y2 y3
addDigitLeft _ (Four _ _ _ _) = error "This should not happen, since it's handled in addLeft"

-- Add an element to the right of a FingerTree
addRight :: a -> FingerTree a -> FingerTree a
addRight x Empty = Single x
addRight x (Single y) = Deep (One y) Empty (One x)
addRight x (Deep l m (Four y1 y2 y3 y4)) = Deep l (addRight (Node3 y1 y2 y3) m) (Two y4 x)
addRight x (Deep l m r) = Deep l m (addDigitRight x r)

addDigitRight :: a -> Digit a -> Digit a
addDigitRight x (One y) = Two y x
addDigitRight x (Two y1 y2) = Three y1 y2 x
addDigitRight x (Three y1 y2 y3) = Four y1 y2 y3 x
addDigitRight _ (Four _ _ _ _) = error "This should not happen, since it's handled in addRight"

This left Joshua feeling defeated. He didn't even know what he meant to the other party. In the Tigian tribe, powerful female Tigans never lacked for male companions, who could be kept for mating by a female based on their military merit.

What was he then? Just a regular bed partner? To be played with when in the mood and then left in the corner (this was only because he was in the Insect tribe and couldn't be returned to the government or transferred to other females).

As Joshua's mind raced, he didn't recover until Junye lifted him out of the water.

Junye wrapped him in a towel, and the confused look in Joshua's eyes as he gazed at him made Junye feel somewhat moved.

Furthermore, the water Junye had prepared was apparently too hot for the males, as Joshua's body was reddened by it, looking incredibly enticing.

A cut to the abdomen was just a minor injury for a robust, military female like Junye, who had long since recovered. If not for the fear of getting pregnant again, she wouldn't mind having a go with the young master.

From the growth of the young, Junye deduced that he must have mated with the young master during his awakening. Considering the success rate of a single mating, Junye decided to hold back after feeling a bit too hands-on with the towel.

When Junye's claws suddenly retracted, Joshua was taken aback and looked up to her, only to find her expression strangely serious — as serious as it was when changing the obviously stained bedsheets before.

She had just pinched him, right? That area... wasn't it some kind of hint?

As Joshua looked at him so innocently, Junye suddenly felt guilty about his actions and coughed, saying, "It's late, and you've been holding the eggs all day... cough, rest early."

Was it truly no hint?

"Okay," Joshua obediently agreed, turned around, and carefully picked up the egg next to the bath.

Junye who witnessed the scene of picking up the egg (interpreted as 'fat soap'): "..."

This bathroom is indeed a bit too hot.

Once Joshua confirmed that Junye didn't intend to mate with him, he sympathized with the egg.

Similarly discarded by that unfaithful female Tigian, but fear not, from now on I'll give you the affection they would not.

And so, Junye watched as Joshua brought the eggs to bed, handling them gently.

Seeing the neglected incubator on the nightstand, Junye felt complicated: "Are you sure you want to incubate these yourself?"

Because of some indescribable feelings, Joshua was lying on his back away from Junye, who half-sat behind him. Hearing her question, he turned his head in surprise. Only certain flying beasts need to incubate eggs. The life force of Insect tribe younglings is very resilient; even if they are born in the wild, they can grow and hatch on their own unless they encounter predators or natural disasters.

It seemed Junye lacked even basic knowledge about the Insect tribe, not knowing that their eggs didn't require incubation, and even during their time in the bathroom, she mistook what he was holding for an edible beast egg!

Thinking this, Joshua held the eggs even closer. With such an unreliable female parent, it was all up to him whether the younglings could survive to hatch.

Junye: "..." What's with that defensive look? I'm not interested in snatching eggs to incubate.

"As long as you want to incubate, do so," Junye lay down and said to the male Insect showing his pale shoulder blades, adding, "Just don't crush them."

Joshua was silent. The female's knowledge was worse than he thought. The shells of Insect eggs are pretty hard; he couldn't even crush them completely if he lay on them.

Joshua hesitated whether to enlighten her but felt a shiver as her claws slid down from his waist.

Is it happening?

Joshua bit his lower lip, his heart pounding, his cheeks burning hot.

The female encircled his stomach, pressed her body against his back, and then placed her hand on... the one he was using to hold the egg?

"???"

Junye gently kissed Joshua's blond curls and whispered, "Sleep now."

"…"

Joshua: "Okay…"

Disappointed, not even a cuddle?

But! If you don't intend to do it, why are you pressing so close?!

Joshua's face remained hot for a while.

That night passed without words.

The next day, in the energetic early morning, accidents are hard to avoid.

Joshua noticed it earlier than Junye himself. By the time Junye felt something and woke up, Joshua had already moved the egg aside and excitedly burrowed under the covers.

As the sky brightened, Junye felt a moment of daze.

It was quite warm, even hot... Had the sun already risen, or was the air conditioning set too high? It feels scorching... and feels like someone is licking whipped cream.

"…"

Licking?!

In an instant, Junye regained his senses. He barely breathed for a moment, then he immediately retreated, pulling the male Insect out of the covers.

"Cough cough..." As Joshua came out from under the covers, he coughed, his face flushed with an abnormal color.

Junye saw the shiny wetness on the male's lips, his mind roaring with thoughts, forget the damn whipped cream!

Joshua, covering his mouth and coughing, sneaked glances at Junye. It was one thing to do something furtively, but being seen...

His face grew hotter, and Junye's gaze upon him was a mix of shame and irritation.

Instinctively, Joshua wanted to dive back under the covers to hide, and he did just that.

1) 제목
한국 역사학의 역사와 유교주의

2) 키워드
유교, 한국 역사학, 실학, 성리학, 도덕주의, 합리성, 실증주의, 중화주의, 기자조선, 역사 서술

3) 브리프
유교 도덕주의와 합리성이 교차하는 한국 역사학 소개

4) 구성
- 유교와 한국 역사학의 발전
- 성리학의 영향력과 변화
- 실학의 등장과 역사학에의 적용
- 중화주의 대 민족주의적 접근

5) 전체 요약
한국 역사학은 유교적 도덕과 합리성의 기반 위에서 발전했다. 성리학은 강력한 중화주의와 유교 도덕을 강조했으나, 명나라가 청나라에 의해 멸망하면서 실학이 부상하였다. 실학은 실증주의를 바탕으로 한국적 정체성 탐구로 이어졌고, 기존 성리학 중심 역사 서술에 변화를 가져왔다.

6) 용어설명
**성리학**: 중국 송나라 시기 발달한 유교 철학의 한 분파로 도덕주의를 강조하는 사상 체계.  
**실학**: 조선 후기에 나타난 실증주의적 학문 경향으로, 기존 성리학의 이론보다는 실제로 적용 가능한 실용적 학문을 추구함.

DIM SHARED arr(10)

SUB QuickSort(left, right)
    IF left < right THEN
        pivot = arr(INT((left + right) / 2))
        i = left
        j = right
        
        DO
            WHILE arr(i) < pivot
                i = i + 1
            WEND
            WHILE arr(j) > pivot
                j = j - 1
            WEND
            
            IF i <= j THEN
                SWAP arr(i), arr(j)
                i = i + 1
                j = j - 1
            END IF
        LOOP UNTIL i > j
        
        QuickSort left, j
        QuickSort i, right
    END IF
END SUB

evalIntExpr :: IntExpr -> Int
evalIntExpr (Leaf x) = x
evalIntExpr (Add e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 + evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Sub e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 - evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Mul e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 * evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Uminus e) = - (evalIntExpr e)

evalIntExpr :: IntExpr -> Int
evalIntExpr (Leaf n) = n
evalIntExpr (Add e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 + evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Sub e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 - evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Mul e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 * evalIntExpr e2
evalIntExpr (Uminus e) = negate (evalIntExpr e)

evalIntExpr (Sub e1 e2) = evalIntExpr e1 - evalIntExpr e2

% Règle pour mettre en relation deux étapes si elles sont connectées par un tronçon
etapeConnectee(Code_E1, Code_E2) :- relier(Id_T, _, Code_E1), troncon(Id_T, _, _, _, Code_E1, Code_E2).

% Règle pour inclure les connexions directes et indirectes
connexionDirecteOuIndirecte(Code_E1, Code_E2) :- etapeConnectee(Code_E1, Code_E2).
connexionDirecteOuIndirecte(Code_E1, Code_E3) :- etapeConnectee(Code_E1, Code_E2), connexionDirecteOuIndirecte(Code_E2, Code_E3).

% Hypothétique : traite un chemin de X à Y avec N tronçons.
chemin(X, Y, N) :- troncon(X, Y), N = 1. % Cas de base, un tronçon est un chemin avec N = 1.

% Si l'on peut construire un chemin de X à Z, et de Z à Y, augmenter N par le nombre de tronçons sur le segment de Z à Y.
chemin(X, Y, N) :- chemin(X, Z, N1), troncon(Z, Y), N = N1 + 1.

% Utiliserait le prédicat externe ou natif 'mod' pour déterminer si N est impair.
trajet_impair(X, Y) :- chemin(X, Y, N), mod(N, 2) = 1.

% Un cas de base où un chemin direct de X à Y existe.
trajet(X, Y) :- troncon(X, Y).

% Extension récursive où un chemin de X à Y existe si 
% il y a un chemin direct de X à Z et un chemin de Z à Y.
trajet(X, Y) :- troncon(X, Z), trajet(Z, Y).

% Un circuit est un cas spécial de trajet où le point de départ 
% et d'arrivée sont les mêmes.
circuit(X) :- trajet(X, X).

The room is bathed in the dull glow of emergency lights, casting long shadows across the array of scientific equipment and the mysterious wooden crate at its center. SARAH JANE SMITH enters, her steps hesitant yet curious.

SARAH
(to herself)
Place gives me the creeps at night...

She approaches the crate, eyeing the SILVER ARMOR contained within. Its craftsmanship is exquisite, almost alien in its perfection.

Suddenly, a MOUSE scuttles across the floor, breaking the silence. Sarah laughs at herself, a mix of relief and embarrassment in her tone.

SARAH
(jokingly, to the armor)
What’s the matter? You’re not scared of a little mouse, are you?

Chuckling, she reaches out and takes the armoured hand in what’s meant to be a comforting gesture. To her shock, the hand grasps back firmly.

SARAH
(shocked and breathless)
What in the world...?

The ARMOR’S EYES begin to glow ominously, a soft mechanical WHIRRING filling the air. Sarah tries to pull away, but the grip is unyielding.

SARAH
(terrified)
DOCTOR!

The camera ZOOMS IN on Sarah’s petrified face, then CUTS TO BLACK abruptly.

SFX: CLASSIC DOCTOR WHO CLIFFHANGER STING

CUT TO:

“DOCTOR WHO” in bold letters against a backdrop of space. The iconic theme tune plays over the credits.

INT. CYBERMAN LAIR - NIGHT

The lair is stark, lit by harsh, artificial light that casts long, ominous shadows across the room. At its center stands the CYBERPLANNER, a more imposing Cyberman, surrounded by various technological paraphernalia. SARAH JANE SMITH is held captive, fear and defiance mixing in her expression.

THE CYBERPLANNER
(planfully)
Your resistance is irrelevant. Shortly, you will be liberated from the burden of emotional objections. Humanity's illogical reliance on such weakness is what has led your species to this juncture.

SARAH
(defiantly)
People aren't weak because they have feelings. That's what makes us strong. The Doctor will stop you, you'll see.

The CYBERPLANNER pauses, regarding Sarah with a cold, analytical gaze.

THE CYBERPLANNER
(dismissively)
The Doctor is inconsequential. Our plans are far beyond the thwarting capability of any one individual.

Just as the Cyberplanner finishes speaking, THE DOCTOR bursts into the room, a mixture of concern and determination on his face.

THE DOCTOR
(boldly)
I'd say that's a matter of perspective. And from where I'm standing, your perspective is about to change dramatically.

The Cyberplanner turns to face the Doctor, its expression unreadable beneath its metallic exterior.

THE CYBERPLANNER
(coldly)
How convenient... 

A beat of silence hangs in the air, fraught with tension. It's clear that a significant confrontation is imminent.

SARAH
(urgently)
Doctor!

The Doctor gives Sarah a reassuring look before turning his attention back to the Cyberplanner, ready to confront the threat head-on.

CUT TO BLACK.

SFX: CLASSIC DOCTOR WHO CLIFFHANGER STING

CUT TO:

“DOCTOR WHO” in bold letters against a backdrop of space. The iconic theme tune plays over the credits.

FADE OUT.

module Task05 where

import Prelude hiding (($))
import Test.QuickCheck

tribonacci :: Integer -> Integer
tribonacci n
  | n <= 0 = 0
  | n <= 2 = 1
  | otherwise = helper 0 1 1 (n - 2) -- We start with a=0, b=1, c=1 and need to perform n-2 iterations
  where
    helper a b c count
      | count == 0 = c -- Return c when count reaches 0
      | otherwise = helper b c (a + b + c) (count - 1) -- Perform the next iteration

main :: IO ()
main = do putStrLn "Some simple test cases:"
          quickCheck (tribonacci 5 == 7)
          quickCheck (tribonacci 6 == 13)
          quickCheck (tribonacci 10 == trib 10)
          putStrLn "Checking further cases, while being careful to not go too high:"
          quickCheck (\(NonNegative n) -> (n < 25) ==> (tribonacci n == trib n))
